  "analysis": "Overall performance was essentially flat on spend but meaningfully weaker on revenue efficiency. Total spend was $151,527.38 and revenue was $158,208.90, yielding an ROI of 4.41%. Across the week, the first half (2/9–2/11) was solid (ROI 16.69%, 16.52%, 13.25%), then performance deteriorated sharply from 2/12 onward (ROI 6.05% on 2/12, 3.20% on 2/13) culminating in a major loss day on 2/14 with $24,494.47 spend against $17,626.84 revenue (ROI -28.04%). Spend peaked on 2/12 at $28,914.71 right as ROI started to break, suggesting budget was not throttled quickly enough when efficiency softened.\n\nWinners/losers by topic + bid strategy show that “roas val” produced the highest upside on small, targeted pockets: longsleevecroptops + roas val (ROI 250.74% on $10.09), nflgear + roas val (143.42% on $14.90), and birthdaypresents + roas val (138.54% on $33.29) were the best performers (low spend but very strong ROI). The biggest underperformers were concentrated in max val / max num and a few roas val topics: datenightstyle + roas val (ROI -100% on $11.66), partygames + max val (-96.33% on $24.00), slowcookingtools + max val (-94.87% on $17.36), and longsleevecroptops + max num (-94.64% on $26.50). At the strategy level, bid cap was the strongest overall (ROI 12.72% on $15,458.12), while max num was negative (ROI -7.98% on $33,061.96) and both cost cap (ROI 0.61% on $43,183.77) and max val (ROI 1.29% on $49,083.11) were near breakeven.\n\nNext week, reallocate budget away from the segments that drove the late-week collapse and toward the few strategies/topics showing repeatable efficiency. Specifically: (1) Scale bid cap cautiously (it delivered $17,423.87 revenue on $15,458.12 spend, ROI 12.72%) and expand it into adjacent audiences/topics where feasible; (2) keep “roas val” running but restructure it: the top ROI combinations are promising but are too underfunded to matter—raise budgets/volume caps on the best topics (nflgear, birthdaypresents, bestvacuumdeals, longsleevecroptops) while enforcing tighter guardrails (min ROAS rules, cost controls, and faster cut logic) to avoid the -100% pockets like datenightstyle; (3) pause or heavily constrain max val in the worst topics (partygames, slowcookingtools) and audit max num broadly (overall ROI -7.98%), keeping only ad sets with proven positive contribution; (4) implement day-of-week pacing protections given the 2/12–2/14 degradation (e.g., automated rules to cut spend when ROI drops below 0% intraday, and step-down budgets heading into historically weaker days).\n\nWeek-over-week, spend decreased slightly by $1,315.10 (-0.86%), but revenue dropped sharply by $24,823.79 (-13.56%), driving ROI down by 15.34 percentage points (-77.67%). Efficiency deterioration is also visible in unit metrics: CPC rose by $0.20 (+133.33%) and CPR rose by $1.02 (+48.34%), while clicks fell by 611,227 (-58.87%) and results fell by 24,141 (-33.27%) despite impressions being slightly up (+127,035; +0.85%). By strategy, cost cap contracted significantly (spend -$34,933.57; -44.72% and revenue -$41,071.52; -48.59%) with ROI down 7.59 pp (-92.56%); max val expanded (spend +$11,761.50; +31.51%) but ROI fell 25.29 pp (-95.15%), indicating added budget went into lower-quality traffic (CPC +$0.31; +310%). The only clear positive momentum was max num, which scaled with better efficiency (ROI +9.21 pp, results +7,300; +197.4%, and CPR -$1.53; -33.7%), though it still ended the week negative overall (ROI -7.98%), so it needs tighter controls rather than broad scaling."
